      Oh McKinsey
   =20
 =20
Come on:The Securities and Exchange Commission today charged Puneet Dikshit=
, a partner at a global management consulting firm, with illegally trading =
in advance of a corporate acquisition by one of the firm=E2=80=99s clients =
in September.The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, filed in federal district court i=
n Manhattan, alleges that in the course of providing consulting services, D=
ikshit learned highly confidential information concerning The Goldman Sachs=
 Group Inc.=E2=80=99s impending acquisition of the consumer loan fintech pl=
atform GreenSky Inc. =C2=A0According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, in the=
 days leading up to the acquisition announcement on Sept. 15, 2021, Dikshit=
 used this information to purchase out-of-the-money GreenSky call options t=
hat were set to expire just days after the announcement. =C2=A0The SEC=E2=
=80=99s complaint further alleges that Dikshit violated his firm=E2=80=99s =
policies by failing to pre-clear these options purchases, which he sold on =
the morning of the acquisition announcement for illicit profits totaling ov=
er $450,000.=E2=80=9CWe allege that Dikshit breached duties to his employer=
 and his client by misusing their confidential information for his own fina=
ncial gain,=E2=80=9D said Joseph G. Sansone, Chief of the SEC Enforcement D=
ivision=E2=80=99s Market Abuse Unit. =C2=A0=E2=80=9CThanks to our trading a=
nalysis tools, we were able to move swiftly to hold him accountable for his=
 actions and protect the fairness of our securities markets.=E2=80=9DHe als=
o faces criminal charges. The =E2=80=9Cglobal management consulting firm=E2=
=80=9D is of course McKinsey & Co., which Goldman hired to help with due di=
ligence and then integration for=C2=A0its acquisition of GreenSky. Dikshit =
was a partner =E2=80=94=C2=A0a partner! =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the assignment, a=
nd, once Goldman formally hired McKinsey to help with the integration =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0making clear that a deal was imminent =E2=80=94=C2=A0he alleged=
ly did this:At 3:41 p.m. on September 13, using an IP address associated wi=
th Consulting Firm, Dikshit purchased 212 GSKY call option contracts with a=
 $10 strike price and a September 17 expiration date at a cost of approxima=
tely $2,100. These highly speculative call option contracts=C2=A0would expi=
re worthless if by September 17 the price of GSKY did not increase approxim=
ately 13% from its September 13 closing price of $8.85 per share to the str=
ike price of $10 per share.The next day, Sept. 14,=C2=A0Goldman=E2=80=99s b=
oard approved the transaction and Dikshit allegedly sold=C2=A0some longer-d=
ated GreenSky call options to raise cash to buy thousands=C2=A0more Sept. 1=
7 $10-strike options for $21,000. Gotta maximize leverage, you know? The ne=
xt day, Sept. 15, Goldman announced the deal, GreenSky closed up 53% at $11=
.90, and, allegedly:After the pre-market announcement, between 9:34 a.m. an=
d 9:35 a.m., Dikshit, using an IP address associated with Consulting Firm, =
placed orders to liquidate the 2,481 GSKY call option contracts he had purc=
hased in his account on September 13 and 14, which he had acquired at=C2=A0=
a cost of approximately $23,100. Those orders were executed between 9:35 a.=
m. and 9:42 a.m. for proceeds of $449,128.=C2=A0Also  not ideal:The consult=
ant made his trades using an account in his name and one in his spouse=E2=
=80=99s name, according to the SEC. Evidence of Dikshit=E2=80=99s insider t=
rading was found on his work computer, prosecutors said. On the day before =
the GreenSky deal was announced, Dikshit used Google to search: =E2=80=9Cwh=
at happens to options when company is acquired=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cgreens=
ky market cap.=E2=80=9D He also used it to check his broker=E2=80=99s web p=
age for information about $10 GreenSky call options, they said.Three weeks =
later, after news of suspicious trading in GreenSky options, Dikshit used h=
is McKinsey computer to run searches about Rajat Gupta=E2=80=99s insider tr=
ading conviction.If I were Goldman I=E2=80=99d be mad! Not because of the =
=E2=80=9Cmisusing their confidential information=E2=80=9D stuff; that=E2=80=
=99s embarrassing but it=E2=80=99s not like Dikshit=E2=80=99s alleged tradi=
ng=C2=A0drove up the price Goldman had to pay for GreenSky or anything. Jus=
t because of the operational incompetence! This is the guy you hired to adv=
ise you on your integration of a financial services firm and he=E2=80=99s (=
allegedly) out there=C2=A0buying short-dated out-of-the-money call options =
on the target of a merger he=E2=80=99s working=C2=A0on? In his own name? Fr=
om his work computer? Come on! This is the most basic rule of insider tradi=
ng, that you don=E2=80=99t do that. This is not legal advice but it is =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0it's just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s best practices, you know?=
 If you=E2=80=99re a management consultant you should be a bit more strateg=
ic.
