      Oh Kimbal
   =20
 =20
This weekend Elon Musk tweeted a poll asking if he should sell $20 billion =
or so of Tesla stock. Twitter voted =E2=80=9Cyes.=E2=80=9D Tesla=E2=80=99s =
stock was down 4.8% on Monday; it was down again yesterday. Also on Monday =
 I offered a list of 18 discussion questions about the poll. Here=E2=80=99s=
 another one.19. What=E2=80=99s up  with this?Kimbal Musk=C2=A0sold=C2=A0Te=
sla Inc.=C2=A0shares a day before his brother, Chief Executive Officer=C2=
=A0Elon Musk, launched his now infamous Twitter poll.Kimbal, a Tesla board =
member, sold 88,500 Tesla shares on Nov. 5, according to a=C2=A0filing=C2=
=A0that day after the market close. He sold the stake at an average price o=
f $1,229.91 per share via JPMorgan, the filing says. That amounts to about =
$109 million. The shares sold represented about 15% of Kimbal=E2=80=99s equ=
ity stake, excluding options.I suppose the specific questions would be (1) =
do you think that, when Kimbal sold his stock, he knew that Elon was going =
to tweet his poll the next day, and (2) if he did know, would that be bad? =
Be careful with the second one! For one thing, it is not clear that the pol=
l =E2=80=94=C2=A0a binary choice of =E2=80=9Csell=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cdon=
=E2=80=99t sell=E2=80=9D tweeted out to millions of random people on Twitte=
r =E2=80=94=C2=A0was material nonpublic information. Arguably the informati=
