h stock is worth about $50. If you buy both stocks they=E2=80=99re worth $1=
00.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now you combine those businesses into o=
ne company, Company AB. If you buy stock in Company AB and both businesses =
work out, your stock will be worth $200. If A works out and B doesn=E2=80=
=99t, though, your stock will be worth $0: The negative cash flows from B w=
ill offset the positive cash flows from A. Same if B works out and A doesn=
=E2=80=99t. If neither works out, the cash flows will be negative $200 and =
your stock will still be worth zero. Your stock in company AB is worth =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0again assuming that A and B are independent 50/50 propositions =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0about $50. Whereas the stock in A plus the stock in B was wo=
rth $100. By combining the businesses you have destroyed $50 worth of value=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not real business advice! There a=
re lots of good reasons to combine two businesses. Businesses are not actua=
lly independent bets with exogenous probabilities. If Business A has a real=
ly good manager and=C2=A0B does not, combining them and putting A=E2=80=99s=
 manager in charge of both might improve B=E2=80=99s odds of working out. (=
This is especially true if A and B are <em>not</em>=C2=A0uncorrelated bets,=
 but are similar businesses where lessons from A carry over to B.) Or maybe=
